<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFF01FD56FDDF5565" blockId="16.[145,762,717,831]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01FD56FEDB54B9" box="[145,265,718,739]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFE85FD55FE3754B9" authorityName="E. J. O. Hartert" authorityYear="1901" box="[277,485,717,739]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFE85FD55FE5C54B8" box="[277,398,717,738]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Synallaxis</emphasis>
omissa
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFDEAFD55FD2154B8" box="[634,755,717,738]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFDEAFD55FD2154B8" box="[634,755,717,738]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFF01FD74FEF8555B" box="[145,298,748,769]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01FD74FEF8555B" box="[145,298,748,769]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFEA8FD74FE08555B" box="[312,474,748,769]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFEA8FD74FE08555B" box="[312,474,748,769]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. caquetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFD85FD74FD51555B" box="[533,643,748,769]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dissors">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFD85FD74FD51555B" box="[533,643,748,769]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. dissors</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the forehead, supercilium and face Vandyke brown (221) without any trace of rufous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFF01FCF0FDC852CB" blockId="16.[145,761,872,1170]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01FCF0FECE5527" box="[145,284,872,893]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Description:</emphasis>
Throat sepia (119); breast and abdomen hair-brown (119a) with or without cinnamon (39) elements; flanks olive brown (28) varying individually to hair-brown (119a); rectrices sepia (119); back hairbrown (119a) with variable traces of amber (36); crown, forehead, supercilium and face Vandyke brown (221); wing-coverts amber (36); remiges Vandyke brown (121); bill length 
<quantity id="A7779B37C848FFEAFEC0FBA6FE20520E" box="[336,498,1086,1108]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3699999999999999" metricValueMax="1.51" metricValueMin="1.23" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" unit="mm" value="13.7" valueMax="15.1" valueMin="12.3">12.3–15.1 mm</quantity>
; bill depth 4.0– 
<quantity id="A7779B37C848FFEAFD30FBA6FD27520E" box="[672,757,1086,1108]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" unit="mm" value="5.1">5.1 mm</quantity>
; wing length 
<quantity id="A7779B37C848FFEAFEB1FBC5FE175229" box="[289,453,1117,1139]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.99" metricValueMax="6.49" metricValueMin="5.49" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" unit="mm" value="59.9" valueMax="64.9" valueMin="54.9">54.9–64.9 mm</quantity>
; tail length 58.0– 
<quantity id="A7779B37C848FFEAFD1FFBC5FD275229" box="[655,757,1117,1139]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.45" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" unit="mm" value="74.5">74.5 mm</quantity>
, with ten rectrices (see Tables 7, 8).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFF01FB2DFDDD5384" blockId="16.[145,761,1205,1503]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01FB2DFDD75291" box="[145,517,1205,1227]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
Distribution: 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFEA3FB2DFDD75291" authorityName="E. J. O. Hartert" authorityYear="1901" box="[307,517,1205,1227]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">Synallaxis omissa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is entirely allopatric with 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFF41FB4CFE8152B3" box="[209,339,1236,1257]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF41FB4CFE8152B3" box="[209,339,1236,1257]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFEF4FB4CFDD452B3" box="[356,518,1236,1257]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFEF4FB4CFDD452B3" box="[356,518,1236,1257]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFD87FB4CFD1052B3" box="[535,706,1236,1257]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFD87FB4CFD1052B3" box="[535,706,1236,1257]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. caquetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFF01FB6BFF2E535D" box="[145,252,1266,1288]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dissors">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01FB6BFF2E535D" box="[145,252,1266,1288]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. dissors</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, being restricted to the area east of the right bank of the 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C848FFEAFEB3FA89FE4A537D" box="[291,408,1297,1319]" country="Brazil" name="Tocantins" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Tocantins</collectingRegion>
River, in south-eastern Pará and northern and western 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C848FFEAFE72FAA8FDB3531C" box="[482,609,1328,1350]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Maranhão</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="18987642C848FFEAFDFFFAA8FD6F531C" box="[623,701,1328,1350]" name="Brazil" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. The geographic range of the species is restricted to the Belém AE [as defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFE3BFAF5FD9153D9" author="Haffer J" box="[427,579,1389,1411]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" pagination="131 - 137" refId="ref16171" refString="Haffer J. 1969. Speciation in Amazonian forest birds. Science (New York, N. Y.) 165: 131 - 137." type="journal article" year="1969">Haffer (1969)</bibRefCitation>
] and all records of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFF3BFA14FEF353FB" box="[171,289,1420,1441]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF3BFA14FEF353FB" box="[171,289,1420,1441]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the state 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C848FFEAFE3DFA14FDF153F8" box="[429,547,1420,1442]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Maranhão</collectingRegion>
are attributable to 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFF01FA33FF2E539A" authorityName="E. J. O. Hartert" authorityYear="1901" box="[145,252,1451,1472]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01FA33FF2E539A" box="[145,252,1451,1472]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Distribution represented in 
<figureCitation id="F8B42A57C848FFEAFDD7FA32FD6153E5" box="[583,691,1450,1472]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="6.[145,226,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[174,1428,226,1449]" captionTargetId="figure-26@6.[145,1428,195,1478]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing the distribution of sequenced individuals, phylogenetic time tree and plumage analyses for the Synallaxis rutilans group. The areas of endemism recognized by Silva et al. (2005) are highlighted on the map, and distribution points are numbered in accordance with individuals in the tree. The phylogenetic time tree is based on 1539 bp of concatenated ND2 and COI genes. Posterior probability values and the 95% HPD are indicated at each node. Thr, throat; Rec, rectrices; For, forehead; Sup, supercilium; Fac, face; Win, wing-coverts; Rem, remiges; 1st, first colour (main colour); 2nd, second colour (variation ±); 36 (e.g.), colours in Smithe’s catalogue; *, specimen damaged or immature; **, specimen analysed without Smithe’s catalogue; MPEG A, spirit collection specimen; dark grey circles in map and patches in table, specimens with grey plumage pattern; light grey circles and patches, specimens with olive plumage pattern; black circles and patches, specimens with rufous plumage pattern; purple star, type locality of S. r. dissors; red star, type locality of S. r. caquetensis; red star with white spot, type locality of S. r. confinis; blue star, type locality of S. r. amazonica; blue star with a white spot, type locality of S. r. tertia; orange star, type locality of S. r. rutilans; yellow star, type locality of S. r. omissa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530669/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Figures 1</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="F8B42A57C848FFEAFD7BFA32FD2B53E5" box="[747,761,1450,1471]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="10.[145,224,1191,1213]" captionTargetBox="[145,1401,195,1151]" captionTargetId="figure-187@10.[145,1425,195,1151]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 4. Plumage distribution and geographic variation in the Synallaxis rutilans group. Dark grey circles, specimens with grey-patterned plumage; pale grey circles, specimens with olive-patterned plumage; black circles, specimens with rufous-patterned plumage. Concerning intermediate individuals, any specimen with rufous present on the upperparts was classified in the ‘specimens with rufous-patterned plumage’ group. *Illustrations of birds with the typical plumage of: S. caquetensis (on the left); S. dissors (centre above); S. omissa (right). Area of endemism (AE) and distribution of species of the Synallaxis rutilans group: purple, Guiana EA, S. dissors; red, Napo EA, S. caquetensis; orange, Xingu EA, S. rutilans; yellow, Belém EA, S. omissa; and green, Inambari EA, blue, Rondônia EA and turquoise, Tapajós EA, S. amazonica. *Illustrations from del Hoyo J, Elliott A, Sargatal J, Christie DA, de Juana E, eds. 2017. Handbook of the birds of the world alive. Barcelona: Lynx Edicions (retrieved on 10.11.2017 from http://www.hbw.com)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530681" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530681/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">4</figureCitation>
by yellow colour of the Belém AE.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFF01F99AFD6350EB" blockId="16.[145,761,1538,1714]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01F99AFEC5504D" box="[145,279,1538,1559]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Remarks 4:</emphasis>
According to E.J.O. 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFD84F99BFD115042" author="Hartert EJO" box="[532,707,1538,1560]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" pagination="71" refId="ref16198" refString="Hartert EJO. 1901. [Synallaxis omissa n sp.]. Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club 11: 71." type="journal article" year="1901">Hartert (1901)</bibRefCitation>
, the 
<typeStatus id="BF348870C848FFEAFF01F9B9FF2B506D" box="[145,249,1569,1591]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFEB3F9B9FDBA506C" authority=", AMNH" authorityName="AMNH" box="[291,616,1569,1591]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFEB3F9B9FDD1506D" box="[291,515,1569,1591]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Synallaxis omissa</emphasis>
, AMNH
</taxonomicName>
523598, an adult female, was collected by Joseph Beal Steere (1842–1940), on 
<date id="14311012C848FFEAFEC1F9C6FE3A5029" box="[337,488,1630,1652]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" value="1897-07-19">19 July 1897</date>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFE64F9C6FD2B502E" author="LeCroy M &amp; Sloss R" box="[500,761,1630,1652]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref16479" refString="LeCroy M, Sloss R. 2000. Type specimens of birds in the American Museum of Natural History. Part 3: Passeriformes: Eurylaimidae, Dendrocolaptidae, Furnariidae, Formicariidae, Conopophagidae and Rhinocryptidae. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 257: 1 - 88." type="journal article" year="2000">LeCroy &amp; Sloss (2000)</bibRefCitation>
highlighted that the correct year of collection was 1879 [not 1897, as reported by E.J.O. 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFE6CF904FD7050E8" author="Hartert EJO" box="[508,674,1692,1714]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" pagination="71" refId="ref16198" refString="Hartert EJO. 1901. [Synallaxis omissa n sp.]. Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club 11: 71." type="journal article" year="1901">Hartert (1901)</bibRefCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFF01F945FAAA570C" blockId="16.[145,762,1757,1902]" lastBlockId="16.[809,1424,197,342]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFF01F945FEC350A8" box="[145,273,1757,1778]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Remarks 5:</emphasis>
The original description of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFDC0F945FD6950A9" box="[592,699,1757,1779]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFDC0F945FD6950A9" box="[592,699,1757,1779]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cited the 
<typeStatus id="BF348870C848FFEAFF2CF964FF3F514B" box="[188,237,1788,1809]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">type</typeStatus>
locality as Pará, 
<collectingCountry id="18987642C848FFEAFE20F964FE245148" box="[432,502,1788,1810]" name="Brazil" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(E.J.O. 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFDDFF964FD39514B" author="Hartert EJO" box="[591,747,1788,1809]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" pagination="71" refId="ref16198" refString="Hartert EJO. 1901. [Synallaxis omissa n sp.]. Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club 11: 71." type="journal article" year="1901">Hartert, 1901</bibRefCitation>
). Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFEA5F883FDAB516A" author="Paynter RA Jr &amp; Traylor MA" box="[309,633,1818,1840]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" refId="ref16908" refString="Paynter RA Jr, Traylor MA. 1991. Ornithological gazetteer of Brazil. Cambridge: Harvard University Press." type="book" year="1991">Paynter &amp; Traylor (1991: 66)</bibRefCitation>
considered this to be more precisely defined as ‘Belém’, and designated the coordinates 0127/4829 (USBGN) for the precise location. Restriction of the 
<typeStatus id="BF348870C848FFEAFB6DFF5DFAE25680" box="[1277,1328,197,218]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCD9FF7CFC6C56A3" box="[841,958,228,249]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCD9FF7CFC6C56A3" box="[841,958,228,249]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to Belém, Pará, was corroborated by 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFCB9FE9BFBA15742" author="Papavero N &amp; Overal WL &amp; Teixeira DM &amp; Hinshaw J" box="[809,1139,258,280]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" pagination="87 - 269" refId="ref16833" refString="Papavero N, Overal WL, Teixeira DM, Hinshaw J. 2008. The travels of Joseph Beal Steere in Brazil, Peru and Ecuador (1870 - 1873). Arquivos de Zoologia 39: 87 - 269." type="journal article" year="2008">
Papavero 
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFC33FE9BFC33574D" box="[931,993,258,280]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">et al.</emphasis>
(2008: 133)
</bibRefCitation>
and is consistent with the species distribution east of the right bank of the 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C848FFEAFCB9FED8FC4A570C" box="[809,920,320,342]" country="Brazil" name="Tocantins" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Tocantins</collectingRegion>
River based on the specimens we studied.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFCB9FEE6FCA552EB" blockId="16.[809,1426,382,1201]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9FEE6FC7A57C9" box="[809,936,382,403]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Remarks 6:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFC24FEE7FBA357CE" author="Peters JL" box="[948,1137,382,404]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" refId="ref16928" refString="Peters JL. 1951. Check-list of birds of the world, Vol. VII. Cambridge: Harvard University Press." type="book" year="1951">Peters (1951: 91)</bibRefCitation>
stated that ‘The majority of the specimens of this 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFBDAFE05FB6657E9" box="[1098,1204,413,435]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="lack">race lack</taxonomicName>
any trace of rufus on the head and underparts; occasional specimens however are coloured exactly like 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFB2EFE43FA8257B5" box="[1214,1360,474,496]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFB2EFE43FA8257B5" box="[1214,1360,474,496]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. r. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, and in fact, as previously reported, the underparts of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCB9FD80FC4D5477" box="[809,927,536,557]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9FD80FC4D5477" box="[809,927,536,557]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFC47FD80FB935477" box="[983,1089,536,557]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFC47FD80FB935477" box="[983,1089,536,557]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can appear similar in respect of those specimens of the latter with cinnamon (39) colour on the breast and abdomen. However, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFAB6FDCDFA435431" box="[1318,1425,597,619]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFAB6FDCDFA435431" box="[1318,1425,597,619]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed by the plumage of the head and 
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFAD6FDECFA4354D3" box="[1350,1425,628,649]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">contra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFCB9FD0BFC6C54F2" author="Peters JL" box="[809,958,658,680]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" refId="ref16928" refString="Peters JL. 1951. Check-list of birds of the world, Vol. VII. Cambridge: Harvard University Press." type="book" year="1951">Peters (1951)</bibRefCitation>
, among all of the 
<specimenCount id="7689FD5BC848FFEAFB12FD0AFAF754F2" box="[1154,1317,658,680]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" type="generic">317 specimens</specimenCount>
analysed by us (including those in the Museum of Comparative Zoology, where Peters was curator while preparing his 
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9FD76FBA85559" box="[809,1146,750,771]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Check-list of birds of the world</emphasis>
in 1931–52), we have not located any individual of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFBD8FC95FB615579" box="[1096,1203,781,803]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFBD8FC95FB615579" box="[1096,1203,781,803]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the coloration of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCD5FCB4FC6D551B" box="[837,959,812,833]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCD5FCB4FC6D551B" box="[837,959,812,833]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(or 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFC7EFCB4FB8E551B" box="[1006,1116,812,833]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dissors">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFC7EFCB4FB8E551B" box="[1006,1116,812,833]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. dissors</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFB07FCB4FAEA551B" box="[1175,1336,812,833]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFB07FCB4FAEA551B" box="[1175,1336,812,833]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. caquetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) on the head. In other words, none of the specimens showed any trace of amber (36) or cinnamon (39) on the head and face, whereas all individuals of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFA9FFC10FA5955C6" box="[1295,1419,903,925]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFA9FFC10FA5955C6" box="[1295,1419,903,925]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCB9FC3FFC4C55E1" box="[809,926,934,956]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dissors">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9FC3FFC4C55E1" box="[809,926,934,956]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. dissors</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFC4FFC3FFB5955E6" box="[991,1163,935,956]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFC4FFC3FFB5955E6" box="[991,1163,935,956]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. caquetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
analysed by us were well marked in this respect. It is important to note that 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCF3FC7CFC0155A3" box="[867,979,996,1017]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCF3FC7CFC0155A3" box="[867,979,996,1017]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCB9FB9BFC4D524D" box="[809,927,1026,1048]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9FB9BFC4D524D" box="[809,927,1026,1048]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has been distinguished to some extent as a unique biological entity by use of a unique vernacular name. Whereas the English name of all other taxa within the 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFC3AFBC6FBF75229" box="[938,1061,1118,1139]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFC3AFBC6FBF75229" box="[938,1061,1118,1139]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is ruddy spinetail, sooty spinetail was used for 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFBBCFBE5FB4A52C8" box="[1068,1176,1149,1170]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFBBCFBE5FB4A52C8" box="[1068,1176,1149,1170]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by del 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C848FFEAFB7CFBE5FCA252EB" author="Hoyo J &amp; Collar NJ" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" refId="ref15532" refString="del Hoyo J, Collar NJ. 2016. HBW and BirdLife International illustrated checklist of the birds of the world. Volume 2: Passerines. Barcelona: Lynx Edicions." type="book" year="2016">Hoyo &amp; Collar (2016)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
